<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title></title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">WWC0005</span></p><h1 style="margin:12pt 0pt 3pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold"> the Association of School and College Leaders</span></h1><h1 style="margin:12pt 0pt 3pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Underachievement in education by white working class children</span></h1><h1 style="margin:12pt 0pt 3pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></h1><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Association of School and College Leaders (ASCL) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">represents </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">over 17,000 heads, principals, deputies, vice-principals, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">assistant heads, business managers and other senior staff of maintained and independent schools and colleges throughout the UK. ASCL has members in more than 90 per cent of secondary schools and colleges of all types, responsible for the education of more </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">than four million young people. This places the association in a unique position to consider this issue from the viewpoint of the leaders of secondary schools and of colleges.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ASCL welcomes this inquiry and is pleased to contribute, though the time allowed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for assembling the evidence, coinciding as it did with the summer vacation period, has meant that there has been little chance to discuss it with representative school and college leaders.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There are a few points that ASCL would wish to make, however, whic</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">h can be summarised as:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.41pt; padding-left:18.29pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the problem is real and significant</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.41pt; padding-left:18.29pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">it is not of schools’ making</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.41pt; padding-left:18.29pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">schools and colleges can and do address the issue (in different ways in their different contexts), but</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.41pt; padding-left:18.29pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">they cannot solve it by themselves, and</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.41pt; padding-left:18.29pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">if there is a focus on t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">his group it may lead to other groups slipping back.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h3 style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">problem </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">is real and significant</span></h3><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The most recent GCSE figures</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> from the Department for Education (DfE)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> show that in 2012-12 30.5% of White British pupils on free school meals (FSM) achieved 5 A*-C gr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ades. The equivalent figure </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">for White</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> British pupils not on free school meals was 62.7%. This shows clearly the effect of relative poverty.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The effect was less marked in other ethnic groups. The proportions of pupils on FSM achieving 5 A*-C were: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">51.8% </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Asian pupils, 45.6% of Black pupi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ls and 67.2% of Chinese pupils</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. It appears that t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he attainment of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">white students</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is polarised by social cl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ass to a greater extent than</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> other ethnic groups</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, with those from w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">hite working class homes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">being </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the lowest attaini</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ng group.</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The low achievement levels of many white working class children has been masked by the success of middle class white children in the English school system</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, with analysis concentrating on ethnicity and taking insufficient account of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">social </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">background</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and poverty.</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">7</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The situation has not improved in recent years, with a general increase in success not helping to close the gap between middle and working class children. Arguably the gap has widened. </span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">8</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The effect may be due in part to factors o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">er than</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the pove</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rty of families</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, as white working class pupils are more likely to live in disadvantaged neighbourhoo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ds with high levels of poverty.</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> This is likely reinforce negative feeling and pressures.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h3 style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The problem</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> is not of school</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> making</span></h3><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">9</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Children spend only </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a small proportion</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of their time in schools, and patterns of behaviour and expectation are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to a large extent </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">set before they </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">begin to attend school. Parental factors such as low literacy levels, feelings of marginalisation, poor engagem</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ent with the community, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">low aspirations of their children’s education</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, poor housing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and social deprivation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> all strongly affect a child’s chance of success</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">10</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A study commissioned by the Department for Education found that a wide range of “stress factors” i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n the home resulted in a sharp dip in pupil performance at school.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> These included parental </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">divorce or constant arguing among mothers and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> fathers after the age of seven, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">having large numbers of brothers and sisters, parents with poor literacy skills and bei</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ng frequently disciplined in the home</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">11</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">These factors are not limited to working class families of course, but they are correlated with low income. P</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">overty </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">certainly </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">play</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a major role in the underachievement of white working class pupils. Low incomes, be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nefits and the pressure of not having any money </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">undermine </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the stability of family life. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Schools report higher incidences of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">low self esteem, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">drug and alcohol abuse, poor </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">mental health, safeguarding issues, learning difficulties, exclusion, prison, a lack o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">f parenting skills in families </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in socially deprived areas and caught in poverty</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Such middle-class ‘givens’ as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">regular bedtimes and family meals</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> are clearly less likely, less possible, in such families</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">12</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">chools </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">report</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that white working class families </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> often </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the hardest </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">draw into </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the life of the school and to engage </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">their children’s learning. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is clearly a need for central government to provide </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">strong leadership in addressing issues of poverty and under-achievement</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, which has been felt to be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">absent in recent years under government of all parties.</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h3 style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Schools and colleges can and do address the issue </span></h3><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">13</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A case study of schools in Lambeth</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> found that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the headteachers interviewed:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.41pt; padding-left:18.29pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Provide a culture of achievement w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ith a positive can do attitude.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.41pt; padding-left:18.29pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Pro</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">vide multiracial schools where the diversity of pupils’ backgrounds and circumstances are celebrated. Whatever their background, schools ensure that they succeed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.41pt; padding-left:18.29pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Monitor pupils’ progress by ethnicity and social background</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Pupil tracking is rigorous. The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">data enables senior staff to have the confidence to challenge assumptions about and attitudes to pupils’ performance</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.41pt; padding-left:18.29pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Regard liaison with parents as vital in the school’s drive to raise achievement. They have developed genuine partnerships with parents and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the community they serve. School </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">staff was</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> aware that they had to draw parents in for positive reasons as a counter balance for the negative experiences that many had at school themselves.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’</span></li></ul><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">14</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Likewise colleges often pride themselves on being able to help wo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rking class students, who have perhaps reached a level of maturity that is enabling them to break away from a culture of low aspiration, onto a path to success. Many FE and sixth form colleges reach out specifically to such students explicitly to give a se</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cond chance.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">15</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Circumstances differ markedly from place to place, and depending upon the social mix at the particular school</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> or college</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. The situation for a white working class pupil in a school with predominantly of middle class pupils presents different ch</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">allenges from that of working class pupils in a school drawing predominantly from their geographical and social area. It is important that schools are able to decide at their local level what approaches to take, tailoring them to their particular environme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nt and priorities.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h3 style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Schools and colleges cannot solve this problem</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> by themselves </span></h3><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">16</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As noted above young people spend relatively little of their time in education, and are strongly affected by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">home and peer group</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that surround them.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">17</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The problems </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">set ou</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t in paragraphs 9 to 12 above show how difficult it would</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> be for schools </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and colleges </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">make much progress in this area by themselves</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> wider intervention is needed.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">18</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Since 1976, when </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Arnold Weinstock, managing director of the General Electric Company,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">wrot</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e a letter in the Times Education Supplement </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">blaming</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> teachers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">for not preparing pupils for employment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, there has been a tendency to assume that wider failings in society can be blamed on (and therefore potentially solved by) educ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ation. In this case the eff</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ect wa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s to suggest that unemployment is due to poor preparation for the workplace, rather than on there being too few jobs. </span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">19</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Addressing white working class under achievement by setting new targets to schools and colleges, or altering the range and governan</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ce of such institutions, or interfering with the curriculum or the qualification system, is to try to treat the symptom rather than the disease. There is a need to address more fundamental issues of inequality, and to intervene at an earlier stage in a chi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ld’s development to encourage and support </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">parents to value their children's education</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">20</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The education system, though it is part o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">f the solution to society’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> failings, cannot correct them by itself.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h3 style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">If there is a focus on this group it may lead to other </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">groups slipping back</span></h3><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">21</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is a feeling in schools, supported by some local studies</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">White pupils</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> achievement </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">has fallen in recent years while</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">focus has been on other groups.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">22</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">While the real problems of this large group should clearly be addressed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> there is a danger that other groups will then fall back in turn. It is important to accept the point made in paragraph 15 above that it should be up to individual schools and colleges to decide how to strike a balance in their particular area.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">23</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Teachers, a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nd their leaders, want all their students to succeed, and are best placed to decide how to help them to do so.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h2 style="margin:24pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Conclusion</span></h2><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">24</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This is an issue well worth consideration, but it </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is complex and difficult. It requires very careful thought before rushing to judgem</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ent about what are the true causes of the problem and what should be done to address it.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">25</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">But we can conclude that changes in the education service, though some could be made to good effect, will do far less to improve the situation than changes elsewhere i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n society</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. In particular the very wide and widening gap between the wealth of the most and least affluent members of our society is very damaging in this respect.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">26</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">I hope that this is of value to your consultation, ASCL is willing to be further consulted a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nd to assist in any way that it can.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> September 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">References</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Demie, F &amp; Lewis, K, (2011), ‘White Working Class </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Achievement: An Ethnographic Study of Barriers to Learning in Schools’. Educational Studies, Vol 37; 3, pp245-264</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Department for Education, (Jan 2013), ‘GCSE and Equivalent Attainment by Pupil Characteristics in England, 2011-12’ accessible via </span><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/gcse-and-equivalent-attainment-by-pupil-characteristics-in-england"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:none">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/gcse-and-equivalent-attainment-by-pupil-characteristics-in-england</span></a></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Guardian (18th